snippet.textDisplay: I've never heard anyone say anything negative about Dak as a guy, and this isn't about anything like that, but Rob Parker is hitting on something when he points out Dak Prescott's "numbers are hollow, they don't matter."  Numbers can deceive (I'm looking at you, Russel Westbrook).  I'm not going to go as far as Parker and call Prescott a fraud because I don't think he's trying to deceive anyone, but to the eye, Dak doesn't consistently  throw what you'd call a catchable ball.  Too often drilling it to an awkward part of the receiver's catch radius, etc.  Not convinced his leadership is as inspiring as advertised, either.   Dez Bryant for one didn't seem to be too enamored of the balls Dak was serving up back when Dez was still running routes.  This year one of the league's most talented rosters-<del>-the Dallas roster--</del> goes 8-8.   Why?  Can't be all the coach's fault, although Garret rightly took his licks for it.  But at this point Dak has shown what he has to offer.  That's not an insult---it isn't easy to be one of the NFL's elite QB's. Few people in the world can do it.  But if you're J Jones, I'm not sure you pay Dak more than you absolutely have to.

I'm not going to go as far as Parker and call Prescott a fraud because I don't think he's trying to deceive anyone, but to the eye, Dak doesn't consistently  throw what you'd call a catchable ball.  Too often drilling it to an awkward part of the receiver's catch radius, etc.  Not convinced his leadership is as inspiring as advertised, either. But if you're J Jones, I'm not sure you pay Dak more than you absolutely have to.
